\section{Introduction}
This document summarizes a discussion on the interconnections between Hamming codes, number theory, and concepts in quantum cosmology, focusing on extremal functions, characteristic sequences, and their potential relevance to the wave function of the universe.

\section{Odious and Evil Numbers}
We begin by defining two classes of numbers based on their binary representations:

\begin{definition}
An \textbf{evil number} is a non-negative integer whose binary representation has an even number of 1s.
\end{definition}

\begin{definition}
An \textbf{odious number} is a non-negative integer whose binary representation has an odd number of 1s.
\end{definition}

These classifications, while primarily of mathematical interest, serve as a starting point for our exploration of binary representations and their connections to other areas.

\section{The Hamming Sequence and Binary Counting}
The Hamming sequence, also known as the Regular Number sequence, is defined as follows:

\begin{definition}
The Hamming sequence consists of numbers of the form $2^a \cdot 3^b \cdot 5^c$, where $a$, $b$, and $c$ are non-negative integers.
\end{definition}

This sequence (1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 8, 9, 10, 12, 15, 16, ...) is related to binary counting through its construction using powers of prime factors.

\section{Hamming Codes and Sphere Packing}
Hamming codes are a class of linear error-correcting codes that have optimal properties in terms of sphere packing in the space of binary strings.

\begin{definition}
The Hamming distance between two strings of equal length is the number of positions at which the corresponding symbols differ.
\end{definition}

In the context of coding theory, sphere packing refers to finding the maximum number of non-overlapping spheres (defined by the Hamming distance) that can fit in the space of all possible words of a given length.

\section{Connections to Quantum Cosmology}
The concept of finding extremal functions over metric spaces, as seen in the optimality of Hamming codes, may have relevance to the wave function of the universe proposal in quantum cosmology. This connection lies in the search for solutions that minimize or maximize certain functionals related to action principles or other variational problems.

\section{Characteristic Functions and Gould's Sequence}
An interesting connection was noted between a sequence of characteristic functions and Gould's sequence for divisors (A001414 in OEIS). This sequence is related to the number of odd divisors of integers and has various number-theoretic connections.

